data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings are:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Test class: constructor replaces [SetUp], Dispose replaces [TearDown]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        // Per-test setup (runs before each test)
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Per-test teardown (runs after each test)
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` naturally replace `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`.
- `IClassFixture<T>` ensures the fixture is created once and shared across all tests in the class — matching `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- If your setup/teardown is async, implement `IAsyncDisposable` and use `IAsyncLifetime` instead.
